python#/logic/boolean-expressions"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Boolean expressions"}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://docs.trinket.io/getting-started-with-python#/logic/combining-boolean-expressions"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Combining Boolean expression"}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Don’t forget theses! They become very useful when combined with conditionals and we will revisit them in a later exercise!"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"exercise","properties":{"id":"5","title":"Variables"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As you may have noticed with the previous examples, in some instance, the numbers are assigned to a variable (e.g., temperature). Variables in computer science always contain a name and a value.There are two ways to do variable assignments:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Type the name of the variable, then "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"="}]},{"type":"text","value":", then the value as we have seen before."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Ask a user for an input. You can do so by using the "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/taking-input-in-python/"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"input"}]},{"type":"text","value":" function"}]},{"type":"text","value":". This functionality can be useful when you need to share code with a with other researchers with minimum coding experience as it will slowly guide them through assigning values. Remember that a value can be many things - including text!-, which can make it valuable to promp someone for a file path. In practice, however, you will find that you will most often assign variable using the "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"="}]},{"type":"text","value":" sign between name and value. "}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Question:"}]},{"type":"text","value":" Create the variables "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"temperature"}]},{"type":"text","value":" and "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"units"}]},{"type":"text","value":" and assign them the values of "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"14"}]},{"type":"text","value":" and "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"degC"}]},{"type":"text","value":" respectively. "}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"codeblock","properties":{"id":"01_04"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Using the "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"="}]},{"type":"text","value":" sign for variable assignment. Remember how to enter strings in Python!"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This brings an interesting question. We assigned an integer to one variable and a string to another. But as we will see, not every operation can be performed on every type of variables. If you want to know what your variable is, all you have to do is "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"type(variable)"}]},{"type":"text","value":". Doing this now would be silly but as we start playing with more toolboxes, knowing what you have assigned to your variable or what a function returns will become more and more important! "}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"exercise","properties":{"id":"6","title":"Words and Letters"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Now that we have talked about numbers and booleans, let’s have a discussion about text, otherwise known as strings. You have seen a string already (“Hello World”). Let’s see how we can add (yes, add) strings and perform other operations. Look at the lessons below (although keep in mind that in Python3, which you will be using, the print command requires parentheses.):"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://docs.trinket.io/getting-started-with-python#/changing-text/changing-text"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Changing Text"}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://docs.trinket.io/getting-started-with-python#/changing-text/slicing-text-part-1"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Slicing Text, part 1"}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://docs.trinket.io/getting-started-with-python#/changing-text/slicing-text-part-1"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Slicing Text, part 2"}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"There are many other operations that you can do on strings:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Concatenation: "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\"I love \" + \"geoscience\""}]},{"type":"text","value":" will give you "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\"I love geoscience\""}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"You can check whether a word is in a sentence. "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\"are\" in \"Rocks are a geologist's dream\""}]},{"type":"text","value":" will return the boolean "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"True"}]},{"type":"text","value":". You can also use the "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":".upper()"}]},{"type":"text","value":" and "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":".lower()"}]},{"type":"text","value":" functions to make the match more flexible. In fact, there is an entire way of looking for matched in strings called "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_expression"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"regular expression"}]},{"type":"text","value":" or regex. Regex is not unique to Python. In fact, you could almost consider it its own separate language inside Python to create more flexible queries. "}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Question:"}]},{"type":"text","value":" Consider the following sentence: ‘The law of superposition, a major principle of stratigraphy, states that within a sequence of layers of sedimentary rock, the oldest layer is at the base and that the layers are progressively younger with ascending order in the sequence.’"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Write a code that will retrieve the word ‘superposition’."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"codeblock","properties":{"id":"01_05"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Remember that Python uses zero-based indexing and that the end must be inclusive.  "}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]}],"data":{"quirksMode":false}},"frontmatter":{"id":1,"title":"Module 1: Introduction to Python","description":"In this module, you will learn how to write basic Python code. Make sure that you go through the material provided before attempting the exercises. You have two solutions to attempt the exercise (1) Write directly into the console and click `run code`. You will be told whether your get the correct number. If stuck, you can ask for a hint or show the solution. Note that the first time you do this, a cloud server will be set up and it may take some time. Also do not navigate away from the code block (e.g., by opening another exercise) as this will stop the execution. (2) Attempt this on your local machine and use the Show solution tab to verify that you did the exercise correctly.","next":"/module2","pre